animal.description:
Suki is a gorgeous white dog with black spots and big, sweet brown eyes. Her coat is soft and silky.
 Suki is a gentle, low-energy sweetheart who loves leisurely walks and relaxing. She is quite independent, no-nonsense, and spends the majority of her days resting and napping. Because of partial hearing loss, she has a loud Woof, so she would do best in a free-standing house rather than an apartment or a condo. 
She is completely house-trained and can be left unsupervised and uncrated with no issues. Suki has been the only pet in her foster home, so her ability to live with other dogs, cats, or young children is unknown. However, on our daily walks around the neighborhood, she is great when meeting other dogs, has a couple of toddler-aged human friends who give her full-body hugs and treats while she wags her tail, and even has a neighborhood kitty friend who walks up to her and flops on his back while she sniffs and nuzzles him. 
We have had a couple of doggy playdates, and Suki wears out pretty easily and has trouble settling with another dog around. She would do well as an only dog, but may be able to live with a calm canine companion. Suki occasionally barks to communicate with her people that she wants food or to go outside. 
Most details of her history are unknown, but it is clear that she has had multiple litters of puppies. In just a few short months, Suki has transformed from timid and depressed to happy and bright-eyed. This strong and gentle girl now wags her tail, gives kisses, and loves being petted.
Suki is an absolutely adorable dog, and will make a wonderful companion in her forever home. She just needs a loving, caring home where she can relax, continue to blossom, and lead a secure and happy life.
 Suki was surrendered to a rural shelter.
 Read more about Suki on the Independent Animal Rescue website at https://animalrescue.net/dogs/d-20-170/.

I am a female Husky/Cattle Dog mix.  I am about 6-7 years old and weigh approximately 56 lbs.  I am spayed, heartworm negative, current on shots, micro-chipped and on flea/heartworm prevention.  I have also had a negative fecal.  My adoption is $200.

My owner passed away and his elderly mother can no longer take care of me.  I am really hoping that I can get a new home pretty quickly!  I am a bit shy (hence the spelling of my name). 

Please email for an adoption application.  Once the application is approved, we will arrange for you to meet and adopt. 

We do not adopt out of state.
Due to many bounced checks, we now require that adoption donations be cash only.  However, if you make a general donation to the organization (not associated with the adoption of a pet) we do accept checks and paypal.  If you are unable to adopt right now, won't you please make a donation to help care for the pets?  THANK YOU!!

animal.description:
Sweet Bruno came to Animal Friends Society as an owner surrender. His owner could no longer care for him. Bruno is approximately 3 years old.  He lives with other dogs and a couple cats in his foster home and does fine with them. 

Bruno is a shy boy who takes time to warm up. He is looking for a family that will be patient with him as he learns to trust them.  Once he does, he is happy to cuddle, sit on your lap, and go for walks. He also needs a faimly who is willing to be patient if he has accidents as he learns the routine of the going out schedule. 

Bruno is neutered, microchipped, heartworm tested (pending), up to date on vaccines, and has been started on a monthly flea and heartworm preventative..

Bruno's adoption fee is $250.00.   Animal Friends Society is a small 501(c)(3) group that uses adoption fees to care for the current and future fosters in our care and to continue our mission of spaying and neutering.

For more information on Bruno, or to request an application, please visit animalfriendssociety@hotmail.com. No phone calls.

animal.description:
Riko is a 10 year old Terrier mix.  She is up to date on shots, spayed, heartworm negative and weighs in at 10lbs.  

Riko came to APAC almost naked due to fleas and poor nutrition. Her hair is returning.  She has some hearing and vision loss.  She can see shadows and that is enough to see her human 6ft away and run to them.  Don't let all that fool you. Miss Rico is the most confident and independent girl you could meet. She uses the doggy door with no problems.  She loves to wander the yard and and uses her nose to tell her what is going on.  She maneuvers the house easily and following her human to "help".  Rico will bark to let her wishes be known, like time to eat, time to snuggle and hey the doggy door is closed. She loves to dress up in pretty clothes. 

Rico hasn't been with children under 10 but enjoyed the ones she has met.

Her adoption fee is $125.  If you are interested in meeting Rico, please send your application to myhappytail@yahoo.com.  Applications are found under the How to Adopt menu on our website at www.myhapptyail.org

animal.description: Sitter Needed: 1/15/21-1/17/21 Alexa's puppy dog eyes will have you giving her belly rubs in no time. This snuggle queen will find a way to burrow into the best spot on the couch with you. She is very content to lounge on the sofa for hours, and her cute snorts will let you know she is happy. When not in lounge-mode, Alexa would love to join you on a car ride, or tag along to hang at your favorite lunch spot. She gets excited by tennis balls and does zoomies around the yard to show you she wants to play. She is happy to entertain herself with toys and bones while you do your work. Alexa loves to meet new people and dogs, wagging her tail and wiggling that big body. She likes to greet people with a lick on the face. She is especially good at using a sad puppy face and her big, pretty eyes to get the attention she wants - usually a belly rub, her favorite activity! She loves going on walks, and does an adorable prance. She is a great sleeper, if a bit of a bed hog. She is fully house-trained, and very comfortable in a crate. Alexa would do well in a house with adults or older kids. She's also been friendly to other dogs on walks, so should get along well with them. She is undergoing heartworm treatment, at APA!'s expense, and is recovering. Come meet your new best friend - let her win you over with her puppy dog eyes!

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

AdoptaGSD.org

Please consider that some of these dogs have been abandoned or ignored by their previous owners, having little interaction with someone who cares about them.

When adopted, they will need time to adjust to the changes in their life.

Hi, my name is Leslie, and I was transferred from a rescue where I was surrendered when my owner fell on hard times and she had to choose between feeding the kids or feeding my pups and me, and we lost. Since then, some of my pups have found homes, but my girl Sophey and I arrived, and we are looking for our forever homes (separately). I'm a sweet dog, who is underweight, undersocialized, and I've only spent time on leash since arriving at FRGSR, so I need work in lots of areas, including dog socialization, obedience and house manners. I've been a doting mom to my pups, and I've been warming up to FRGSR volunteers very nicely. I would love to find a home with a patient adopter who can show me the ropes on many levels. Until now, all I've known is where I've come from where human attention was sparse at best as well as exposure outside of my home. I have to say, that since arriving at FRGSR, I'm loving all the attention I'm receiving, and my hope is to find a forever home soon, but as a mom, I'm hoping for my daughter Sophey to find her home first! My adoption fee is $350 and if you are interested, please go to adoptagsd.org and submit an online application.

Although we do our best to keep our adoptable animals page as current as possible,the animals you see may already be in an adoption process.

animal.description:
Welcome to the family, sweet Lulu!

Lulu is an adorable 9 months old female American Staffordshire Terrier/ Cattle Dog

mix. She is spayed, fully vetted, vaccinated, healthy, and weighs about 48 pounds.

Lulu and her 4 siblings came to us at 4 months old. At first, she was very timid and a bit shut down towards people, but we noticed very quickly that she was most comfortable around other dogs. We held on to her to help her socialize more and build her confidence while living with another big nurturing dog.

Lulu is pretty perfect. She's on the petite side, very fast, agile, and has been training with her foster mom to run on trails. She is an absolute doll and gets along with small and large dogs, kids, and yes, even cats.

We are looking for an active family with another big dog for Lulu to play with and continue to build her confidence. Lulu is now ready to find her forever home and needs a family that has a home with a large yard so she can run free and play with her toys. Lulu can't be trusted off-leash, being so timid, and will run when she gets scared. In the house, she is gentle and calm, but she needs her daily activity and running to make her happy and at peace.

If interested in meeting Lulu, please submit a completed adoption application found at www.doggiebonez.com so that we can schedule a meet and greet. She can also be found on all of our social media pages IG: @Doggie_Bonez_Inc_ and Facebook: Doggie Bonez.


If adoption isn't an option, please consider fostering one of our pups. We are a volunteer-run non-profit dog rescue and always welcome new short or long-term doggie foster families. We much appreciate the help and time of our fosters. You provide all the love, comfort, and safety of a home, and we supply you with everything else you may need, dog food, dog bed, toys, medical attention (if required), etc. If you are interested, please visit
www.doggiebonez.com
to see all of our available dogs who need a foster family while waiting for their fur-ever home and complete the foster application.

animal.description:
Roomba is a SPECIAL NEEDS, 8 year old, 12 pound neutered male Pekingese who is paralyzed in the back end and needs assistance urinating several times each day. Roomba is very vocal and would not be appropriate for an apartment, condo, or townhouse. Roomba needs a home with a one level living area and tile, hard wood or linoleum floors. His adopter needs to help him embrace his challenges but continue to encourage his independence. Roomba's favorite past times include hanging with his people, being scratched, going for walks in his wheelchair, sunbathing and rolling in the grass. His special needs requirements are assistance in urinating (he will prop himself on a toilet for this), going up and down stairs, and getting on and off your lap. He loves his independence and is very capable in scooting at a rapid pace or using his wheelchair during outings. Roomba has even figured out how to work sliding into his movement to get places quickly. Roomba wears clothes to help protect his lower extremities from abrasions. He dislikes a drag bag as it inhibits his ability to move easily. Roomba is not appropriate for children. 

If you wish to be considered for this animal, please download an application at http://fallstonanimalrescue.org/adopt/ or email fallstonrescue@aol.com to request one. It can take up to 2 weeks to process an application; we suggest following up by email on the status if you have not received a reply within 3-5 days. We are an all-volunteer based rescue and we ask for your patience if we are slow to respond.

Please understand that we fit the dog with the home we feel is best suited and will accept multiple applications for one dog. We have strict requirements for families with children under 10 since many of our dogs are grumpy and may not do well with children. Some dogs will have fence requirements, while others may not. It is preferred you are within a 2 hour drive from our Rescue Center in Fallston, MD and preference will be given to local applicants.

A pet is a lifetime commitment and it is our duty to do our very best to place them correctly the first time around. We do not take the adoption process lightly. Thank you for choosing to adopt not shop!

animal.description:
Bruno is a 9 year old mix rescued from a puppy mill. This chubby boy is now happy, social, and friendly. When he came into rescue he was pretty sick with constant vomiting and lethargy . He had been vomiting whole chickens in addition to various parts of chicken (beaks, talons, feathers, wings etc). He was rushed to our vet the moment he came in due to the non stop vomiting. We discovered he was previously fed the live sick chickens on the farm where he lived so they wouldn't have to buy dog food . As a result he currently has no clue what dog food is and isn't eating great despite being offered dry and canned. He is much happier now and feeling better though, so he's on the right track. He loves people and will happily follow you around and sit when asked. Due to his history of being fed live animals ,he will not be placed with cats or other small animals. He is good with other dogs, but can get jealous if they others are getting more attention than him. 

He will come fixed, chipped, vaccinated, and heartworm tested negative. 
***If you are serious about adopting, you must first complete and submit an application on our website. We will not do anything without a completed application. Do not contact us through pet finder or emails us as All info is contained here***

Please be sure to read all about our organization before you apply to adopt. If you are serious about adopting you must complete an application on our website. There is information on our petfinder home page and our website www.phoenixanimalrescue.com . Our adoption fee for adult dogs is $450. We will not adopt a pet to you if all of your current pets are not spayed/neutered. This is a non-negotiable policy of Phoenix Animal Rescue

animal.description:
Meet Cleo!  She came to us from a family that didn't have enough time for her because of really long work hours.  She spent most of her time in a crate without receiving enough exercise or training.  She is now in a foster home where she is getting both.  She is a dog with lots of energy so her new family must be active and willing to play ball or take long walks.  Cleo is crate trained, getting much better on leash and LOVES to play fetch.  She is being fostered in a home with other dogs and cats.  She does enjoy chasing the cats so a home without is probably best.  Cleo is a friendly girl that will thrive with a family that can give her the structure every puppy needs.  If you are interested in Cleo please fill out an application at www.placingpawsrescue.org.

BEFORE CONSIDERING A PUPPY FOR ADOPTION:  Please keep in mind that puppies need attention during the day.  They need frequent potty breaks, playtime, socialization and often a mid day meal.  Please consider your daytime schedule before applying for a puppy.

SPAY/NEUTER POLICY:  Our adoption fee covers the puppies spay or neuter at our vet in Libertyville.  If the puppy is adopted prior to the spay or neuter being done you will be required to bring the puppy back to our vet within 30 days for the surgery.

ADOPTION FEE: $400.00 The adoption fee includes all age appropriate vaccinations including rabies, HW test if age appropriate, de-worming, microchip, fecal, spay or neuter, Heartworm and flea and tick preventative.

ADOPTION PROCESS: PLEASE READ CAREFULLY
The first step in the adoption process is to fill out an application online at www.placingpawsrescue.org.
Once we review the applications, those applicants that are thought to be a good match will be contacted as quickly as possibly. We ask that you please be patient with us as we are all volunteers. Then a telephone interview will take place, references checked and a home visit will be conducted. We will then arrange for you to meet the dog. We require that all family members, including current dogs meet the dog prior to adoption.  We put all of the known information in the animals description. If the animal is listed on the website, we are still accepting applications for that animal. We only remove the animal when the final adoption paperwork is signed. The best way to contact us is by email at placingpaws@yahoo.com. It is very difficult for the limited numbers of volunteers to return all calls. Thank you.

Mora ~4 years old. Good with older considerate children and dogs. Cats TBD. Must have fenced yard.

Residents of VA, NC, or SC Click to apply for Mora
Please Note: This link will take you to Blue Moon Shepherd Rescue.

My name is Mora and I'm 4 years old. I'm a long haired shepherd with a beautiful silky coat. My foster mom says I'm a combination of a super model, professional ball player and rocket scientist. I walk well on a leash, enjoy car rides and taking adventures.

I know my basic commands and am very eager to learn new things. I take treats gently from your hand and am learning to be patient and wait for my food. My foster mom says I am very smart and when treats are involved I can train all day. Sometimes my foster mom wonders who is training who. I'm a typical female shepherd so I know my own mind but I am loving and very sweet.

I like dogs and hanging out with my foster pack. I've been to the park on pack walks with other dogs and I did great. I'm learning how to settle when I'm out of my crate and need some supervision but, I am not destructive. I would like to be an only dog so I can get lots of love and attention that I never got when I was a puppy. I love petting and affection.

From my foster mom: Mora is a wonderful girl. She has come so far and learning more each day. She is learning to trust and starting to enjoy life. animal.description:
Meet sweet chocolate BROWNIE.
He's a delightful 10yo lab mix who weighs about 90lbs. We rescued him from the Downey shelter where he was a staff and playgroup favorite. 

BROWNIE is affectionate and loves getting pets and nuzzles his head in your lap asking for more when you stop.  He is very easy on leash and likes short easy strolls. Brownie is good with other dogs and has a confident easy going grandpa vibe and is happy to watch the youngsters play. See additional video of him when he was at the shelter: https://www.instagram.com/p/CG3Fg8zhHUf/ . 

He recently spent a weekend with one of our volunteers who gave him an A+ report with comments like:
 "Unbelievably sweet and gentle! He has such a unique personality. He connects with you like you’ve had him since he was a puppy...He settled quite quickly and made himself comfy. I didn’t catch him trying to get into anything, chew furniture, etc...He is such a cuddle bug, really loves affection and rubs...has a very happy, yet mellow temperament."

BROWNIE has some arthritis which is currently being managed with medication. He is currently at our kennel and while he's settled in with ease, we'd love to see him live out his retirement years in a nice warm home with a soft bed for his joints. 

BROWNIE is neutered, microchipped, and current on shots. If you are in the Los Angeles area and interested in meeting BROWNIE, please fill out our brief online questionnaire (copy and paste link): www.downtowndogrescue.org/adoption-questionnaire

Additional Downtown Dog Rescue information email: adopt@downtowndogrescue.org or call: 818-407-4145

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Meet Eleanor! Born around February 2019, this sensitive, loving girl will likely weigh around 75-80 pounds after she gets adequate groceries.

Eleanor was found wandering the streets of a Dallas suburb. She was dirty, afraid, had scratches on her nose, and had missed too many meals.

Eleanor's happy place is with a sweet, calm, nurturing family that is home with her a lot. She is truly an angel. Sher loves being with her people, and she loves being petted.

She is great with older children. She adores hanging out and relaxing with them. With her family nearby, she enjoys laying in a window seat while looking out into the woods or resting on her bolster bed.

She would be best as an only dog. She seems to have had bad experiences with other big dogs and tends to go on the offensive. She does not like small dogs at all.

Eleanor is house trained. She has basic leash manners. She rides nicely in a car. She is crate trained, but has no need for one.

She seldom barks, only vocalizing sometimes at varmints behind the fence. She happily comes inside when you open the door for her.

Eleanor will be a great family dog. Because she can startle easily and become frightened, she needs a relaxed, serene environment with a sweet, tender forever family. Any children in the home should be laid-back and at least 11 years old.

SPIN Pyrs are all in foster homes in the Dallas/Fort Worth area. Potential adopters are asked to make travel arrangements if they live elsewhere. All SPIN dogs are spayed or neutered, current on vaccinations and on heartworm prevention. Please go to our website www.SpinRescue.org and fill out an application for this great Great Pyrenees!

animal.description:
Luke joined us with his brothers, sisters and mama from South Korea!  He was rescued from the meat trade by Candy Cane Rescue and Animal Rescue Korea was brought to MNGR.  He’s now safe and sound in our care.  A DNA test on Luke's brother showed that Luke and his siblings are 50% Belgian Malinois, 38% Greyhound, and 12% either Deerhound, Wolfhound, or Borzoi…! 

Luke is very sweet, very smart, but also VERY VERY SHY.  He’s looking for someone who will give him time and understanding while he learns that the world is not a scary place. He follows whatever his brothers do and is most comfortable in their company. He’d do great in a home with another dog who can show him the ropes and who wouldn’t mind his puppy antics. He does love to play! Once Luke trusts you, he will almost certainly be a snuggle bug! Right now he is especially attached to his "foster dad" at the adoption kennel, and 13-year-old boy here who likes to hang out quietly with him in his kennel. 

Luke can jump a 5-foot fence. We are ONLY CONSIDERING homes for Luke that have a minimum 6-foot fence. We are ONLY CONSIDERING homes for Luke where he will not be the only dog in the home. Luke needs a dog-experienced person who can keep him safe and help him learn about the world. He would benefit greatly from a shy-dog socialization class. Luke's siblings are doing great in their new homes and coming out of their shells. Luke needs his chance. He is an adorable boy who has a lot of love to give.

animal.description:
Snow White is a 9 year old yellow lab that was on the euth list due to a medical concern, but thankfully made it safe to rescue. She is comfortable in her foster home and receiving all the love she deserves. Snow gets alongs with other dogs and children. She really is well mannered and as sweet as they come! 

Snow White was recently diagnosed with Cushing's disease, which affects her ability to control her weight and fight infections, among other things. She takes a daily pill for Cushings. And she happily takes it wrapped in a small piece of ham. More details will be posted as vets and rescue volunteers find out more about Snow White.

The suggested adoption donation for Snow White is $250. We are a 501c3 organization which means that your donation may be TAX DEDUCTIBLE. Your donation goes toward the high cost of veterinary care for our animals in rescue, as well as providing supportive services to animals in homes.

Information about the adoption process: All adoptions require a completed ADOPTION APPLICATION. Once your application is approved, we will put you in touch with the dogs foster to see if you and the pet are a good match. If so, we will arrange a meeting for you and the pet. The adoptions for all of our animals will take place in the Omaha, NE area and must be done by the adoptive family in person. We do not ship or deliver.

Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dogs needs. If you and the dog are not a good match, we will help you select another dog, or we will keep your approved application on file for 6 months.

To learn about Muddy Paws Second Chance Rescue or donate to our animals, please visit our website at MuddyPawsSecondChanceRescue.com or our Facebook Page.

animal.description:
We loooove Pippa! She is a queen, and we know you will love her too!

8 year old Pippa is a beauty we rescued from Alabama, and she has had the good fortune to go form the pound to a wonderful foster home where she enjoys resting her old bones! 
We don't how this perfect Golden Girl has not been snatched up yet! 

Pippa's foster mom is a teacher and is gone a full work day, and Pippa does really well left alone in her apartment. She is not a high maintenance gal. We have put Pippa on a diet since she came to us very overweight, and that coupled with her typical senior pet arthritis is not a great combination! She is feeling and looking so much better these days! 

This sweet girl's personality is really blossoming, she loves to nudge your hand for pets and she snores while sleeping and snorts like a pig when awake! She is super cute, super laid back, and a really gentle spirit who just needs a forever home in which to spend her golden years. Pippa has never met anyone she didn't like. The only time she gets animated is when she sees a squirrel cross her path on walks! 

Her human like expressions will keep you entertained just like they do her foster mom! Pippa is house trained, quiet, cuddly, loving, and low maintenance. What is not to love?!

Pippa's adoption fee has been fully sponsored by one of her many admirers.

Please submit an application for darling Pippa today!

Maggie is a sweet girl. She is 12 years young. She was brought to us by a foster home to find this dear one her forever home. She would do well in a home where she would be with large dogs- or where she would be the only dog in the home. She is good with children. We will get her teeth cleaned and all shots brought up to date promptly.
Please find our applications and valuable information under 'Adopt a dog'* on our website: *www.beaglesandbuddies.com* and email your application to beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Let us know your preference of appointment day/time and which dogs you are interested in and we will do our best to accommodate and email you the closest appointment available. Please allow us up to a week to get back to you. Most appointments will be Friday-Sunday, 10 am - 2 pm, for an hour.
*Note bring any other dog/s and the entire family to your meet and greet at B&B.* A complimentary training manual is included with each adoption, authored by terristeuben.com. Check out her website - she is fabulous!
B&B is glad to be open during the pandemic. We know the value and comfort of a loving pet companion and are doing our best to help the dogs and folks who need them. We update our website daily and are always rescuing, vetting, rehabilitating, socializing.
* We are accepting applications for volunteers to spend time with our dogs, hang out, sing/read to the shy ones, walk/toss ball with those who go to the playgrounds; cleaning, office work, gardening, and building/repair projects! *
Are you my furrever family?

For further info on the adoption process, please visit our home page and check out the "Adopt a Dog" section, which has thorough instructions. All our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and

fully vaccinated before adoption; they have been wormed, bathed, socialized, walked daily and much loved; each adoptee leaves with a leash, collar, and all medical records.

Our prices are higher than the shelters' because we nurse the dogs through their illnesses and get them needed surgeries and dentals. We also spend time socializing. Furthermore, unlike shelters, rescues do not get financial aid from the government and must rely on donations, grants, and adoption fees. Our fees for adults start at $150 and go up to $750. The higher end is for our most in demand dogs, such as young beagles and other purebred dogs. The lower end is for dogs who have been here a while. For puppies, we may go beyond this and charge $1000. The good news is that, because rescues fall under the "charity" category, the fees for our dogs are officially donations and are therefore tax deductible. You can think of it as donating to a worthy cause and getting a dog in return!

Sponsor Me

Beagles & Buddies must find ways to raise money so we can continue saving dogs. Your tax-deductible donation keeps our rescue kennel operating!

Hours

Friday: 10 am to 3 pm

Saturday: 10 am to 3 pm

Sunday: 10 am to 3 pm

Monday: CLOSED

Tuesday: CLOSED

Wednesday: CLOSED

Thursday: CLOSED



Weekday appointments may be available. We are a small staff and do our best to accommodate your needs. **Note that during COVID, we are not holding open houses on any day. Please email us for an appointment and include your application (found on our website, beaglesandbuddies.com, under "Forms"). Most appointments will be Friday through Sunday, though other days may also be available. We usually schedule one appointment per hour. Allow 1-2 hours for your appointment. Please look at our website and make a list of one or more dogs that you would like to see.

Contacting Us

If you have a question about adopting, giving up a dog, boarding, or volunteering, please visit the appropriate tabs on our
home page.

For more specific questions, call 626-444-9664 (please leave a voicemail if no answer) or email at beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Note that
Emailing
is always preferred!

Thanks!

animal.description:
Hello!  My name is Dugan,  and I'm a male mixed breed born around October of 2018.   

My adoption fee is $175.

Hanover Humane will only be adopting me to a home in Hanover County, Virginia or a locality that is part of the Richmond, Virginia metropolitan area.

I'm happy, smart, active, friendly, and oh, sooo sweet - however, I'm pretty unsocialized with humans and while I'm VERY friendly and cuddly(I really WANT to be with people), I don't really know what to do with myself when I am. Everything is new to me and I'm so happy to be rubbed and petted,  I just need a patient human who's will to show me the ropes and teach me how to be a good boy. I'm smart and very attentive and want nothing more than to please you.  I'm very affectionate and love attention from people. I seem to like other dogs, but my energy vibe and lack of social skills can irritate other dogs. I'm not a good fit for small children as I would unintentionally turn them into human bowling pins. I'd probably be a challenge for an inexperienced first-time dog owner, but for a dog-savvy owner with some previous experience that's willing to put in a little time with me, I'd make an excellent companion and be your best bud for life.

 I've been neutered/spayed, am current on all of my vaccinations (DHLPP, Bordetella and Rabies), tested for heartworms (and am negative) and put on heartworm preventative, and microchipped.  My new owner will receive a month of free pet health insurance at adoption. 

If you are interested in me, please submit an adoption application at www.hanoverhumanesociety.org.

animal.description:
Beary was born in our care. He was adopted out as an 8 week old puppy, but returned a year later. His owner wasn't experienced to work with Beary's newly developing behavioral issues, so she kept him shut in a bathroom for 12+ hours per day. This treatment made Beary worse and we have had to work for 3+ years to reverse the psychological damage it caused.
Since back with Rockstar, Beary had improved, but still had preferences with regard to people. He is a very smart, intelligent dog that calculates and sizes you up the second he sees you. (You can see the gears turning, LOL). We opted to move him to a board and train environment where he could get extended help and more one-on-one training.
Beary is currently residing at our Board & Train facility for behavior modification. Our trainer agrees that Beary is "special needs" with regard to behavior. He requires an experienced dog owner, a strong leader and continual training (One day per week)

Any inquiries for Beary will require numerous discussions to explain Beary's needs and go over your family situation; house/apt, family members in the home, other pets, children, etc... Once you have been deemed a good candidate you will then meet Beary at our Board & Train facility and discuss Beary's needs futher with our trainer. 

Beary is not for first-time-adopters. He is a WONDERFUL dog who was wronged and deserves a good life with a strong leader and someone committed to understanding and working with him FOR LIFE!
SERIOUS INQUIRIES ONLY

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Keller is a special boy looking for a special home. Keller is about 5 years old who has been diagnosed with advanced cataracts, that he has likely had for most of his life. Since they were left untreated for so long, he is not a candidate for cataract surgery, and has very limited vision. However, you would not know it if you met him. He chases his foster siblings around the yard, finds any food that drops on the floor, frequently follows his foster mom around the house, and has figured out how to open the baby gate. The only treatment he needs for his cataracts is eye drops 3 times a week, which he will allow in exchange for a few treats. Keller has also had a few seizures since coming to Norsled. He is currently taking medication and has not had an seizures since starting it. While it sounds like a lot, 99.9% of the time, he behaves like any other dog.

Keller is a happy-go-lucky boy who gets along well with other dogs. He knows "sit", "down", and "in the crate", uses the doggy door when he wants to go outside, and loves to go for walks. He does well on the leash, but because of his visual limitations, needs verbal warnings when encountering steps or other terrain changes. Like most huskies, Keller is smart, food motivated, and independent. He will follow commands if he feels like it, but is usually easily persuaded with the promise of a treat.

animal.description:
Cameron is a very sweet, loving and well-behaved dog looking for her forever home with a fenced in yard! Cameron loves being outside, whether it's in her yard or going for walks. She is still getting used to walking on a leash and does pull some, but with the Easy Walk harness, it's a bit more manageable. Cameron loves being with her people and wants to be wherever her humans are. She'll follow you around the house to be with you and even though she's a bigger dog, she'll climb in your lap and shower you with hugs and kisses. She would prefer to be your one and only pooch in the home.Cameron is not a big eater, but she loves veggies sprinkled on her dry food, especially broccoli, carrots, and green beans, but no peas please. She does great with the cats in her foster home and would do best with someone who is a home body, unless she can go somewhere with you. If you are interested in this sweet girl, you can apply at mpravl.org.

All Mountain Pet Rescue (Asheville) animals are up-to-date on vaccinations, spayed/neutered and micro-chipped before adoption. Contact the foster parent or Mountain Pet Rescue at pets@mpravl.org for more information.

Please note that visual breed identification of companion animals has been proven to be unreliable, so for most of our animals we provide a best guess at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each of our animals as an individual and do our best to describe and place pets based on personality not breed label.

Mountain Pet Rescue is a 501(c)(3) non-profit tax deductible charity (EIN 82-3039637) located in Asheville, NC.

animal.description:
Gino is reserved gentlemen pit mix that is around 8 years old, and is around 80 lbs. He was found without the use of his back legs and after examination it looks like it is a permanent paralysis. He has been at the shelter in a playpen area and taken out to potty twice a day. It seems as though he has some feeling in his bladder but unable to control it completely. The staff uses a sling to walk his back end out and once he gets started he is eager to get moving. He will walk around supported and then will let them know to take the sling off to pee. He is pretty good at emptying his bladder, but may need help to prevent infection. Gino does have his own fitted wheelchair, but the shelter has trouble using it because of the stairs. Gino will require extra attention for sure but we think he is eager to try and can have a good quality of life in a foster home. He will warm up to people in time, loves stuffed animals, and a kong filled with stuffing is his favorite. He is unsure with other dogs right now and we think that is because of his paralysis. We really want to give this guy a chance at a great life. We are looking for a home with no little kids, cats or other dogs.
 
Video of Gino: https://fb.watch/1IZJuRhOU3/

My adoption comes with a leash, collar, durable dog toy & up to $100 of training.

animal.description:
A resident of the Dallas Shelter in January 2020, Lady was adopted, returned and adopted out again the same day. In October she was handed out thru a car window to a homeless man who also didn't want her. A pretty bumpy year for Lady, we're thankful this man saw the wisdom in helping her find a new and forever home through our rescue.

Now thriving in her foster home, Lady has a very sweet temperament but is timid at first; geez, who wouldn't be after being handed off to so many different people? Despite this, Lady is fluent in giving kisses and just recently found the joy of toys! Speaking of joy; she also got to meet Bruser, another foster in this home and wowza...he's the best thing that's ever happened to her! We should mention; Bruser feels the same attraction to her and has never responded this way to any other dog in the home. They play together constantly and have formed a deep bond. We'd love to see them find a home together, if possible. Lady is not a fan of a crate, but she is crate and house trained.

animal.description:
Scarlett is a beautiful dog who is looking for an active family. She would do best in a non urban environment. She can be a bit reactive on leash, but can play with other dogs with slow, proper introductions, but needs to be the only dog in the household. She would love to live on a ranch or farm and have a job to do. Her favorite pastime is fetching.

Foster Notes: 

Scarlett is absolutely lovely. She is super intelligent. She loves people and children (has only been around children 8 years and older, but lots of them). She loves "her people" but is completely welcoming to others. She is friendly and open to strangers and invites them to throw her beloved ball. She absolutely loves to play fetch with her ball and can happily play for hours! She now takes treats gently from your hand and patiently waits for her food. She has very good manners and wants to please. Her super high intelligence and sweetness is obvious to everyone who meets her. She absolutely loves to be outside. She is loyal and just loves people. She is beautiful, quick, and athletic and impresses everyone who meets her. We just love her!

She showed some anxiety traits when she first arrived, like chasing her tail around in a circle when inside. She stopped doing this by day two, although she briefly chased her tail yesterday in a circle when one of our boys moved one of her puppies (this was also inside). She also is slightly obsessed with her ball and asks someone to throw it for her quite a lot. When she first arrived, she would bring us a rock, asking us to throw it for her. We immediately switched her to a ball, but occasionally she will still bring us a rock. I don't think she was used to being inside, as she seems much happier outside. I think she needs a home with direct access to an outside space and a family/person who can devote lots of attention to her. In return she will be incredibly loving and devoted. She is loving, super intelligent, wags her tail a lot, is eager to play and please. 
Scarlett is a spectacular, impressive dog and whoever adopts her will be very lucky!

animal.description: I am a volunteer/foster at VBACAC and just spent two weeks watching Grumbler while his foster dad was out of town. I wanted to share what I learned about this sweet boy. Grumbler was a pleasure to have in my home. He is a velcro dog who will follow you everywhere. He believes he is a 10 pound lap dog and has absolutely no concept of personal space. He is 100 percent house trained and crate trained. Grumbler has some hip issues and did OK on my hardwood floors but he did slip and fall a few times so he would probably do best on carpet (although he does pretty well with stairs). He is a bit of a "bull in a china shop" kind of dog who is clumsy and will occasionally barrel into things. He is playful and loves toys. He seems to like other dogs- a small off leashed dog ran up to him and Grumbler was perfect and wanted to play with him. He is not good with cats. He seems a bit hard of hearing, although he can hear some things. He knows how to use a doggy door and he loves car rides. He doesnt bark a lot- I only heard him bark twice when he was looking out the window and saw something he wanted to alert me of. Grumbler has nubs for teeth and is a pretty messy drinker so keep a towel ready. He is pretty good on a leash. He has some skin issues, which is common with blue pitties so his new family should be able and willing to deal with this. Grumbler is incredibly friendly and loves people of all sizes, although with his size and clumsiness, he would probably do best with older kids as he may knock young kids over. Grumbler is an older guy who is still fun and playful but is also perfectly happy to hang on the couch with you while you watch the Super Bowl. He is receiving his last heart worm treatment on Thursday and is ready for adoption. Please call the Virginia Beach Animal Care and Adoption Center to meet him. 757-385-4444.

animal.description:
***COURTESY LISTING***
For more info about this dog, please contact person listed below.

Duni is a male Australian Cattle Dog and 4 years old.  I took him out of a neglected home in El Paso, TX, where he was tied up on a short rope and wore a shock collar to control his barking.  He received little attention, was malnourished and sunburnt.  He has been in my care since July 2020, in New York City.  I’ve been training him and working on his fears.  He has some basic commands down, sit, stay, lay down, leave it is hit or miss. We play ‘find it’ often, he’s very good at it.  Duni would really like to be around his owner 100% of the time if possible, he’s as velcro as they come.  He has a lot of potential, just needs patience and training.  I have had him meet other dogs while on leash and all (25 or so) have been positive, except one, my other dog.  She can’t stand him, and they fight. I keep them separated and there is peace in the house.  To meet other dogs, the other dog should be extremely well socialized, and tolerant of ill-mannered dogs (Duni is essentially a puppy, but 44lbs).  He can be fear-reactive towards strangers, but counter-conditioning with high reward treats works, it will take time.  I believe he would excel in a single person or couple household, with no kids or other pets.  He doesn’t seem to want a lot of exercise, just to be with his owner.  He is crated when I am away from home and at night.  I want to find the best possible home for this guy. He's neutered and vaccinated. His adoption fee is $150. For more info contact chrispayan@yahoo.com.

Apollo is a 6-month old male puppy born on May 29 and weighs approximately 14 lbs. He probably won’t get much bigger.  His mother died when he and his siblings were born for unknown reasons so they had to be fed by their rescuer.  
Apollo is a very playful little guy and like all puppies can get into everything.  He is a healthy boy who loves to run, is very affectionate and loves to sit on your lap.  . He’s also a very sociable guy, is used to living among multiple dogs, so would do well in a home with a back yard and another dog to play with. 
If you are looking for a real cutie, have lots of patience and understand that he is still a puppy,   you will have yourself a wonderful, beautiful little dog.  Arnold has all of his shots and has been neutered.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website. All of our dogs and cats are in foster homes and we have no paid staff. If you have questions concerning a specific animal, PLEASE fill out an application and the foster parent will be in touch. We will not arrange any home visits with any of our dogs and cats until your application is processed. Please understand our foster parents are precious to our 2nd Chance family; without them we cannot function, so we do our best to not burden them with multiple appointments. Our foster parents will choose their top 3 applications and arrange home visits with these applicants. The adopter will be chosen at that time. The process can take anywhere from a week to a month. We want to make sure our little furry ones are placed in their 'forever home' and never have to go through a rehoming again!Well hello there. My name is Salvador and I know it so don't try to change it!!! I am fearless, I know I am the boss (well in my head anyway)! I love attention. I will not live without another dog to keep me company, they cannot be a bully because that would make me very sad :( I have a bum knee that I am too old to want fixed! No anesthesia risks for me!!!I require a fenced yard and a fur buddy. Only local adopters being considered at this time. If you meet my requirements lets have a date and see if the 'stars align' for us!Please fill out an adoption application:
Adoption application (Dog)
Adoption Application (Cat)

Please understand we do not adopt out dogs to
families with children under the age of 5. We do not adopt dogs to renters. Some dogs will have fence requirements while others may not.

A pet is a lifetime commitment. The dogs and cats in our system find themselves there, for the most part, because their humans did not have the same loyalty to them as they did to their owners. We do not take the adoption process lightly, and will do everything in our power to make sure the animal is placed correctly the first time around for your sake and theirs. Thank you for choosing to adopt not shop!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Hi! I'm Pietro, but everyone calls me Petey, because I'm a little rascal

I'm a one year old American bully mix and baby, I was born to work!

When I was new to Rescue Rovers I was a lot to handle. It took some time to figure me out. They thought I was dog selective and maybe a little crazy, lolol. Luckily, I'm SUPER lovable and pretty much everyone who met me was all "oh Petey, what a sweet boy you are" and "we just need to find you the right people, Petey!"

Then, a couple of weeks ago, one of my foster mom/trainers said "let's give him a try with GRC"

Do you know what GRC is? I did not. But let me tell youit's a.maz.ing. It's my jam. It's the bomb. It's the highlight of my LIFE and I am a superstar at it.

Also it stands for Gameness, Relationship, Control and it's a dog sport. We get to run and pull and climb and tug.

One of the super cool things about it is that you can get an idea of whether a dog would be good at working and you guysI definitely would be. The people I work with say I would excel at all kinds of things, but *especially* Search and Rescue. Can you just imagine? I can see the headlines now - Petey To the Rescue! Petey Saves the Day!

Okay, anyway, that was just a little daydream of mine. Back to real life.

Other important stuff about me

I'm potty trained and crate trained. I can be kind of noisy in my crate but it's important for me because if I'm left unsupervised, I can get a little curious and rambunctious and, well, naughty. I always quiet down after a bit and then I'm a good boy.

I am good with dogs, but they need to have the right energy match for me. I am a bit "much" for many dogs. I do LOVE to play, though! If I'm going to have a doggy sibling in my forever home I will need an owner that knows how to manage energy and interactions. I am not good with cats or small animals.

I am great with humans of all ages, but we're looking for kids over about 12 for me for 2 reasons - first, because I can be pushy with people I feel will allow me to be, and second because people with younger kids often don't have time for the kind of work I will need. If you think your home and kids are different you can definitely apply to meet me and we'll see how it goes.

I'm also super snuggly and a really big lover. I haven't focused as much on what a great cuddler I am in this bio, but you guys - I am the whole package. I'm good looking, smart, athletic and I will keep you warm and feeling loved, too.

What it comes down to is this - I'm really looking forward to my own forever home. I would love to find a home where I can do a job (and/or be a hero, who knows) or a home where I can keep doing GRC. Either way, I don't want to keep bragging, but I am a natural athlete.

And also I promise to be loving and loyal, even if Hollywood comes calling because I'm so handsome and talented I would NEVER leave you.

If you think I could be the guy for you, apply to meet me today at rescuerovers.org

animal.description:
Companion Animal Outreach Society would like to thank you for taking the time to read about Dre. Dre is very dear to our organization. Dre as a special needs dog. Dre is will have continued challenges with pain management and separation anxiety. It is our my opinion that Dre gets as much exercise as possible. We recommend hydrotherapy (swimming) and Holistic veterinary treatments such as acupuncture, chiropractic, and massage therapy. 
Dre needs training we feel like a trainer that is very experienced special needs dogs and especially knowledgeable on separation anxiety would be beneficial 


Dre’s Current medication he needs to be on for life:
Gabapentin 100mg 1-tab bid (every 12 hours) OR tif (every 8 hours)
        This is approximately $30-40/ month
Trazodone 100mg 1-tab bid
        Approximately $33/ month

Dre has a very hard time with food. This is can be a big challenge. He is currently on homemade food or dehydrated food. 
He would be great for someone needing a support dog that he can be with all the time :)



Dre’s Dos and Don’ts

Dos
•	Loves playing tug o war 
•	Loves playing with rubber balls (working on fetch)
•	You can pretty much get Dre to go where he wants with a leash. When he sees a leash, he because overly excited. This can be used when Dre is having a temper tantrum and does not want to get off of beds etc etc or to go outside for bathroom breaks. Use the leash always when Dre seems to be growling or upset. 
•	Loves snuggling and spooning
•	Loves to play with other dogs- can become protective and dominant so ensure he is watched. He makes very loud growling sounds when playing with toys and other dogs but be sure to watch if he becomes to stimulated it can turn into a fight. (Dre has never hurt another animal while in shelter or at my home)
•	Loves to wake up at 3am – this is something that is challenging. While in my care I get up and take him outside and give him a snack then we go back to bed you need to tell him to lay down and go to sleep sometimes you have to raise your voice a little. Unless you will let him in bed with you this is what he wants in the end is to snuggle he goes to be straight away. 
•	Loves walks
•	Loves to be goofy. He reminds me of a bucking horse. 


Don’ts

•	Picking Dre up can be unsafe at times. You need to ensure you are never touching his back end when doing it and to ensure that your face and other limps are no where near his face. I put my arm under is stomach and another arm under is front leg and his head under my arm pit every time I pick him up and put him down. 
•	Don’t let Dre get away with bad behavior such as howling, aggression and getting into garbage or other things he shouldn’t.
•	Nail trims is something that he really hates (but once the he has been on trazadone it may help with that) previous owner always took him to the vet to get done. 
•	Vet clinics are Dres least favorite place. Ensuring he has the most positive experience at any vet clinic is key. Building relationships with vets is very important. 
•	Back end, he does not like anyone touch back there and his legs so please avoid that area at all costs.


Please contact Erica at 587-272-0390 or email president@caosab.ca if you are interested in adopting Dre or have more questions.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Name: Mooshoo
DOB: 04/25/2020
Weight: 25 Pounds
Adoption Fee: $450

Mooshoo is the smartest dog his foster has ever worked with (and she's been around a lot of dogs)! He knows sit, down (lay down), come, stay, and ok (when it's ok for him to exit and enter the front door behind a person) and almost understands and follows the commands drop and kennel. He's house trained. Being such an intelligent puppy, he needs help staying out of trouble. He spends the majority of the day in his crate with productive (training) let-outs. He pulls at the leash but is improving every day in giving his foster his attention when she redirects. He whines a little bit in his crate sometimes, but knows he won't get attention when he does this. It happens less and less often. Initially he barked in the crate, but he discovered that this doesn't work, either, and is a rare occurrence. He is quick to pick up on new habits.

If he's left unattended, even in cordoned off spaces, he will be tempted to find something new to chew on. In fact, he still needs to learn what to do with his chewing urges--until then, anything nearby may be up for grabs (including furniture/walls/doors). His previous family returned him due to guarding a bone, and his current foster hasn't addressed this, although he shows no aggressive behavior. His training sessions are kept short so he doesn't lose focus or get over excited. When he gets over excited he may bark, bite, and jump. He could be a good cuddler, but he needs to figure out how to self soothe his chewing before getting living room rights (with its many temptations).

His perfect match would be someone with a fenced-in yard who is interested in training a very intelligent dog and has the time and patience to do so slowly and is willing to wait for cuddles and free range of the house until Mooshoo can understand what acceptable behavior looks like. He would also do best as an only pet in the home with only adults in the home.

In the meantime if you have questions or are interested in me, please fill out an adoption application at www.ruffstartrescue.org.

An adoption application is the best way to show your interest in an animal.

Please check out our website, www.ruffstartrescue.org for more details and additional pictures on any of our animals!

All Ruff Start dogs and cats are spayed/neutered, up to date on age appropriate vaccines, microchipped, dewormed, and on monthly flea/tick and heartworm prevention (dogs) as well as heartworm tested (dogs).

Ruff Start Rescue is a foster based rescue. Animals are located in homes throughout Minnesota. We do not have a facility where animals are kept.

Ruff Start Rescue Adoption Policies: http://www.ruffstartrescue.org/info/display?PageID=11744

animal.description:
Toby came to the SPCA from the south as he was a stray who showed daily at someone's house in North Carolina and was busy playing with their 3 dogs and running around their backyard.  After several nights of Toby spending the night on their front porch, the thin and dirty dog was saved by this kind lady took him in, got him a nice bath and took him to the vet.  

Toby is a pleaser and he lovingly seeks attention - he really craves human attention and finds it comforting when he is talked to.  He is very friendly, loves to play with safe pet bones, he will sit on command and offer his paw when a treat is involved.  He likes to sleep in a very cuddly, snuggly crate and he likes to get a bone before bed.  And during the day he likes to sit on top of his crate and enjoy the day.  He was on his own for quite a bit running around being a typical hound but now he seems very interested in just pleasing his humans while he was fostered and playing as much as he could.  Toby will alert you with a bark when he wants food or a treat.  He is a very handsome boy with a heart of gold....please stop by to meet this hound dog!  The staff has worked with Toby on his housetraining and he has done excellent and is housetrained now!  Please note Toby is NOT good with cats....but good with other dogs and kids.

animal.description:
Thank you for your interest in dog who needs a new home. Adoption can be one of the most fulfilling experiences in your life and especially in the life of your new canine companion.

A note to those looking at CPR. We have no perfect dogs - but many of our dogs have proven to be perfect for a certain someone. Our job is to find those someone's. Our most successful adopters come to CPR not because they want a dog. They come to us because they want to give a dog a home. We urge all of our potential adopters not to fall in love with a picture. While we like to know what you like in looks, a dog is more than a pretty face. Our goal is to match you with the best possible pet for you and your home. We want to create furever families.

Our descriptions contain all that we know about this dog today. We'll update as more information is known.

Are you looking to adopt within the next 30 days? If so please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and complete the application. You'll find it in the menu on the left hand side. You'll also find a total listing of all our dogs available.

Just browsing but interested in poodles and poodle mixes? Please drop a note to applications@carolinapoodlerescue.org with your name, address and phone # and email. We'll add you to our mailing list.

thanks
the CPR Adoption team

Date into Rescue: 8/7/2020
Reason for being in rescue: Gus was surrendered to a shelter in AR by his family. Carolina Poodle Rescue pulled him from the shelter.
Foster location: Dreamweaver Farms, Pacolet SC
Special Needs? Gus is obese. He is on a special diet with daily exercise to help reduce his weight. Since arriving in rescue he's lost 9 pounds. He is on a prescription W/D diet and needs to continue this. Gus also has bladder stones. These are breaking up with diet and weight loss.
Weight: 15.5 lbs and losing! Gus is on a serious diet!
Height: 12 in
Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Adoption Fee: $299

Fence needed? No

What kind of home would be best for me? Gus is looking for a home with active retirees. He wants to be with people and does not enjoy being crated or being left alone. Gus will be happy with another dog or cat, or as the only. He just wants his people, a quiet life, and lots of lap time. Gus is a dog that does things on his terms. He can be nippy if you try to pick him up and he doesn't want to be held. If you give him time to come to you, he will spend his entire day in your lap. Given his propensity to nipping if he doesn't want to do something, we do not recommend Gus for a home with children or frequent visitors that are children.

What is my personality like? Gus is a happy-go-lucky man who LOVES food. You can tell from his photos that food is Gus's love language. He arrived in rescue at an obese 27 pounds and we're working hard to get some much needed weight off of him. So far he's down to 18 pounds!! As Gus has lost weight, some of his other medical issues have also improved.

We don't know a lot about Gus's life before being surrendered to a shelter in AR, but it must have been quiet. He is okay on a leash, but it is clear he hasn't spent much time walking on one. He does enjoy going for short strolls and will mark everything he can find along the way. Gus is great with other dogs and with cats. He really just wants to be where people are, frequently bumping into his caregivers when they stop walking because he is so close on their heels.

Gus doesn't like to be made things he doesn't want to do. He isn't aggressive, but will be grumpy. He prefers laying inside on a cool floor or outdoors on a shaded patio to any sort of activity you have in mind. Gus does not like crates and will tell you all about it. He will also guard his food in his crate if other dogs walk by.

Gus is looking for a Netflix and chill sort of family that will take him for daily walks.

How do I act when I first meet new people? Friendly

Other tips and tidbits: Gus's estimated birthday is 7/10/2012

House trained? Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

Please note - we do not ship dogs. If you are interested in adopting, please take a look at the distance between the foster home location and your location and make sure you are willing to make that trip. Most of our dogs are at our farm in Pacolet, South Carolina.

To apply, please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and visit the tab on the left that directions you to the online application.

Please note that when screening applications, we look at the entire home and then make suggestions based on what would be a good fit for your home. You are not being screened for a specific dog although we are looking to see what type of dog interests you - poodles or non poodles, color, age, etc. Others here may be a better fit for you. It is very difficult to get to know a living animal from a picture and a short description. Since we are constantly getting in new dogs, this may be a dog not in our listings yet. We want you to be very happy with your new companion and will make suggestions based on what you tell us about you.

Thank you for considering CPR.

animal.description:
Hi Angel world...I want to thank you for saving me!

Even though I am a senior, I have lots of life and love to give!

I am a tiny dachshund at only 14lbs. but my foster mommy said I could add a few pounds.

I was dropped off at a shelter by my previous owner and I was so scared.

But I am confident at my foster mommy's home and have made friends with all her dogsand she has other dachshunds in her home too!

I need some work on house training but my foster mommy keeps a pee pad available and I am good using that if I do not get outside in time...my foster mommy might try female diapers to see how I adjust to those.

I am older so I cannot always hold it like younger doggies do.

The vets think I am 13 years old but I do not act like itI jump up for attention and I beg for food.

I know that is not a great trait but I was not fed properly before so I am learning to stick to my dog food but I sure love dog treats!

I am developing into a sweet companion dog and love to spend time with my humans.

My foster mommy lets me sleep in bed with her and I make myself a little nest with my blankie every night and sleep through until the next morning.

I LOVE comfy places to sleep.

I can get on and off most furniture with no problem so still have my springy back legs.

I love my foster mommy's big fenced yard and love to wander around for a while by walking her fence line at least once per day and that is all the exercise I need.

So I really need a fenced yard to allow me my wander time and for ease of letting me out frequently.

I have a few special needs about being picked up when I am not ready and with resource guarding my food.

I took a good 2 weeks to get used to my foster mommy but then I let her pick me up all the time, but she approaches me so I know she is coming.

If I get startled, I react with a nip/bite.

I have never broken the skin but I do not like getting startled.

I do resource guard my food but that is because I was never fed enough.

I like to eat by myself and away from other dogs and to be let alone to finish.

I will growl at other dogs if they approach my food bowl and if I am picked up while eating, I will nip/bite. A home WITHOUT KIDS is a must for me due to my nervousness and reactivity to certain things.

I really enjoy snuggling up to my human on the couch, in the bed, about anywhere you will let me!

I love belly rubs too!

I do ride great in the car in my booster seat as I love to be able to look outside.

I am not good with strangers initially but if they leave me alone and let me go to them, there won't be any problems.

My foster mommy can tell you how to deal with all of my peculiar qualities so that I can live a long, happy life in a new home.

I will require some patience so know I am not going to adjust in a day or two.

But I wanted you to know I am a very sweet girl and would love to be in a new home soon so that I can get settled into my forever home with my forever family.

Please let Angels know if you would like to hear more about me!

For inquiries, email inquiry@angelsrescue.org

An Adoption Application for this dog can be found and submitted online at http://www.angelsrescue.org/adopt/adoption-forms

Please be sure to like our Facebook page https://www.facebook.com/angelsrescue.

*Some of our animals receive a high volume of applications, and we strive to select the best home for each animal. However, we have many wonderful homeless pets available.

animal.description:
Prince was found as a lost dog in Houston, TX. Thanks to his microchip we were able to find out he was adopted through Montgomery animal shelter, and we were given his owners contact information. Unfortunately his adopters wanted nothing to do with him and the shelter refused to take Prince back into their program.
   That's where we stepped up and gave Prince the chance that he deserves. Prince did not know love, or how to love people, and was very absent. Over the past (almost) 2 years, he has learned what love is and has become a best friend to his rescue foster family. He has learned to look and ask for attention and has done phenomenal in his training.
   Prince loves his tough dog chew toys and playing "fetch" in the backyard. He is the perfect office buddy and loves napping in his comfy dog beds while you work. He has to be adopted in a home as an ONLY PET and we recommend Prince be placed in a home with children 10 +.

   If you are interested in adopting Prince, please click the "More about Rogues Rescue Ranch" button to the right >>> and fill out our adoption application.

I am available for adoption; however due to my breed my adoption will have to be facilitated through a rescue organization. Please see the front desk staff or contact the Shelter at (248) 858-1070 for more information.

Meet Shea! Looking for an active and fun new friend? Shea is a great fella who wants nothing more than to make you smile, keep you company and be your new companion! He is eager to meet people and might even jump up to kiss you...oops! Shea is a happy boy and looks forward to making his new people happy, too! This fella deserves to be in a safe, secure and loving home, one where he is able to live his best life!

The following descriptions describe behaviors that were observed during testing and/or veterinary examination: Evaluated for temperament with 334953 (female) and 334941 (male). Did well with both. Goofy, playful and strong. He jumps on people and can knock down a smaller person. Recommended training basic commands. 10/29/2020

American Pit Bulls are a misunderstood breed; for this reason, we implore adopters to these beautiful dogs to be very vigilant in training and socialization. This breed is very energetic and will need daily exercise. Because of their strength and energy, apartment living may not be the best fit. This breed can be loving, loyal and very smart. 

The above behaviors and personality traits have been observed while at the Shelter. If this animal was relinquished, information is gathered from the owner regarding behavior. Our wonderful volunteers spend time with these animals and give input on behaviors and traits. However, this description may not be all inclusive to how this animal will act in a loving forever home. Introduction to established family pets should be slow and monitored always. The same goes for children and other family members. Adopting a pet is a big decision and should be thoughtful. We suggest researching different breeds to match traits and personalities to your lifestyle. When adopting a pet, please know that this pet will be with you for their lifetime; patience and consistency will make for a successful adoption.

 Her leash manners are excellent, she’s likely housetrained, loves loves loves treats and loves tossing around plush toys. It’s great when a dog can amuse herself with a toy! She seems to prefer smaller dogs and a meet and greet is required if you have a resident dog

Princess is quiet, gentle, easy, and happy to join in with whatever you want to do. Show her a treat and she’ll follow you anywhere!!

A lover of long easy walks followed up with snuggle time our Princess is ready to find her new royal family. 

She’s spayed, up to date with vaccinations, microchipped, and cordially accepting adoption applications.

animal.description:
Hi! I'm Duke. I'm a 7ish year old chiweenie mix. My foster mom describes me as cuddly, affectionate, loving, and people-oriented. My preferred place is in your lap, or laying next to you, or with my head resting on your knee. I will make the rounds in a room, saying hi to every person. I want to be where the action is, but then I like to go to a quiet place when I've had my fill and just chill and nap. I'm a certified oxytocin booster because my foster mom says my one of my very best qualities is my affectionate nature. I'm also loyal and have an easygoing temperament and since I'm a grown-a** dog I know how to behave around the house. As an added perk I'm also clean, and my short hair doesn't shed much. Although I'm a wee bit older, I'm still pretty spunky and I look like a forever puppy - so really its like the best of both worlds! I can't wait to come home to my people, and I hope there's enough room for me in the bed because I like to spoon too.

My adoption fee is $200. This includes a spay/neuter, up-to-date vaccines, deworming, a microchip, a heartworm test, and, if needed, heartworm treatment.

animal.description:
ADOPTION PENDING

WILL ONLY BE AVAIALBLE TO THOSE ON THE BULLDOG WAITLIST 

Hi there! My name is Stefler and I am a 3 (ish) year old cutie pie! 
 My nickname is Grumpy Potato, and yes I do respond to this. (I bring my foster mom potatoes from the kitchen when she is working to let her know I want something)
I enjoy walks two - three times daily (sometimes more) and some backyard time with my foster family as I tend to get bored and rambunctious sometimes and the activity helps keep my energy in check.
I will do just about anything for a treat and I adore beef liver! 
I do sleep in my crate ( but I want a treat to go in there), and my foster mom suggests putting me in my crate when you are not home as I don't like it one bit when my humans leave me.
I LOVE fuzzy blankets, lots of attention, and my toys.
 
My must haves are:
Tough chewer toys,
Sticks, 
Fuzzy Blankets, 
Snuggles, 
head pats, 
Car rides,
and Treats!
 
Things I don't like:
*Plase don't trty to make me jog or run, I am simply not built for that life and I tend to try to slow folks down when they try to do this.
*Please don't mess with my food, blankets, and toys, I tend to guard my resources; To get things away from me, please trade items with me. 
*Please don't crowd me until I am 100% comfortable with you, it makes me very scared and I may try to protect myself.
*Please don't keep me with children for prolonged periods of time, I do not get along with them very well and I have my limits.
*I do like other dogs, they are cool outside on a leash, none are cool inside my house right now (I like my privacy and I am the king of my castle!).
*no pets please, I like to chase things and try to play with them the wrong way.
*no small children please, when they get excited and rowdy it scares me and I don't like them touching me much. Older teenagers and up are more my pace.
* I am reactive towards vets (and ear cleanings, especially); stay with me please as I need comfort and they often use a muzzle for my own safety so I will need lots of reassurance..
animal.name: Stefler

animal.description:
Well bonjour!
 I'm Louis aka ""Louie"". I've got the cutest look that will melt your heart and at my best will give you more love than you knew was possible. I'm a little misunderstood and people like to label me as a bit of puzzle. While that can be true, it's only because I've had such a rough past that trusting humans takes time for me. If you are willing to be patient with me and work on some of the things that I'm not so good at, then you'll see that deep down inside I'm full of love. I'm doing much better now that I'm on a regular schedule. My current foster parents aren't early morning people and I'm alright with that. I do my daily doggy yoga and stretches while they sip on their first cup of coffee and then I'm ready to seize the day. My previous life on the streets was hard but now I've learned to enjoy the daily adventures that the city has to offer living in downtown Toronto. I meet new dogs and people in the elevators and I'm fine with most of them. Except the small yappy dogs that get in my face, I'm not a fan of them. My foster dad is my favourite but I'm getting used to my foster mom too since she's around more during the day, as she works from home. I think she's happy that I haven't chewed on any furniture or her shoes. If they are both around, he's the one I'll go to first for sure. I won't give you much trouble, I'm crate trained for sleeping at night and will actually go there myself when my foster parents are busy doing human things that I'm not interested in. I won't go in the house unless I am having tummy issues because I got new treats or ate something I wasn't supposed to. You see, I'm very food driven and will be with you in the kitchen all the time so when I see a chance to be a bit of a thief then I will take it. But sadly human food doesn't agree with me as much as I agree with it. The same thing happens when you give me overprocessed treats, especially if they have potatoe fillers. Let's stick to freeze dried chicken and pumpkin treats please. Now let's talk about what you can do for me. Please pet me in moderation but give me lap naps everyday to show me you love me. I don't like any kind of grooming or the vet so you are going to have to take some classes from the dogget training program to work on my displeasures. I won't put on any winter gear and will not let you touch my paws. That being said, over the last month my leash skills have gotten a lot better while training with my foster parents so I'm sure we can fix the rest of my quirks! Looking forward to spending time with you in my fur-ever home Love Louis

-Experienced home
- no kids please ( unless they are teens)
Located in Toronto

animal.description:
WE ARE CURRENTLY ACCEPTING SPONSORS INTO OUR SPONSORSHIP/ADOPTION PROGRAM, FOR THE ANIMALS WE HAVE RESCUED WHICH ARE UNADOPTABLE.
THEY ARE SPECIAL-NEEDS, SENIORS, AND/OR HAVE MEDICAL COMPLICATIONS REQUIRING ONGOING VETERINARY CARE.  SPONSORSHIP INCLUDES UPDATES ON YOUR ORPHAN.  Please contact us for more details about our sponsorship/adoption program.

We have a huge debt for lovely little Hermione who was sick on and off again for over a year.  Hermione has recovered from Pancreatitis which took over a year to identify, diagnose, and finally treat, costing us almost $5,000 altogether, from her first 2:30 AM Emergency Room visit and in-hospital stay, and the following visits with two of her other regular vets.  None of the highly skilled veterinarians thought to give her a pancreatic test because the scary symptoms did not resemble pancreatitis !

Hermione is now on expensive "Just Food For Dogs" and also "Hills Prescription I/D Low-Fat Special Diet, and is fed several times a day, with supplements and vitamins.  We need to pay off the debt for saving Hermione's life.  Hermione's life was originally saved from the Orange County Animal Shelter, where she was out of time.  She lived in several foster homes until she ultimately came to live back with us - now permanently.

For more information about Hermione, and to help her, please contact:  theanimalsleftbehind@socal.rr.com  (Also our Paypal donation/sponsorship email address)

animal.description:
OLLIE needs a quiet home without children of any age. He is very fearful of strangers, so if any children visit the home, he is not the dog for you.

OLLIE is a 1-year-old, 28-pound Labrador Retriever mix. From OLLIE's foster guardian: "OLLIE is very affectionate with "his" people but is fearful of strangers. He knows basic commands and loves other dogs, but he does not like cats. He walks well on a leash and requires a couple of walks a day (even if just around the block) or he will get rammy. He loves to play fetch and snuggle. OLLIE is a lap-dog through and through and would be happiest in a quiet home with a loving family or person." WHAT'S NEXT? If you would like to meet, foster or adopt this pet, please fill out our online FOSTER/ADOPTION APPLICATION which can be found in the main menu of our website or at the bottom of this page - simply copy and paste the link into your browser. EASY PEASY! Once we've reviewed your application, arrangements can be made for you guys to meet! It'll be kind of like a blind date! *** This pet is spayed or neutered in accordance with our strict policy wherein all animals are altered prior to adoption. This pet is dewormed, current on vaccines, and started on monthly flea/tick and preventatives. Animal Alliance's policy is that we will adopt dogs younger than 1 year old to families with children under 9 years old. We do not adopt dogs 1 year or older to families with children under 9 years old due to the unknown history of adult dogs. BY APPOINTMENT ONLY: Meetings at our Adoption Center are by appointment only (no walk-ins). An online adoption application is required and must be approved prior to meeting any animals. Adoption appointments are set up by email by our Adoption Coordinator (no phone calls, please). This process ensures our dedicated time to the animals in our care, as well as full attention to adopters at scheduled times. Prior to submitting an application, please see the Animal Alliance Adoption Process for adoption details. To fill out an adoption application, go to: https://www.animalalliancenj.org/fosteradoption-application/
